We are the girlfriends who love to brunch on the weekends. After our Saturday morning workout, we went to @groundcontrolchicago for a vegetarian/vegan treat and Ground Control does a superb job with friendly service! 
We ate heavenly melt in your mouth Coconut French Toast with grilled Pineapple and house made pineapple syrup! It had just the right amount of sweetness. We also savored a healthy version of Southern food filled with flavorful battered fried tofu, scrambled eggs, biscuit with vegan peppery gravy and braised kale. Lastly, we ate every bite of the Sweet Potato Hash with mushrooms, spinach, daiya cheese and an amazing house made tofu marinated in their secret sauce and spices drizzled with vegan crema and sprinkled tortilla strips. This includes a small salad and yummy fresh tomatillo salsa that we poured over the hash, the eggs and everything savory. .

Waller Ave. In college, I was obsessed with the history of Chicago<92>s neighborhoods, and copied articles and statistics from various sources. In a book called <93>Social data for Chicago communities,<94> which was from the 1940<92>s, I found this summary of Austin. PART ONE: <93>In 1835 Henry L. De Koven <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+00B4><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BF><U+00BC>received a federal land grant in Cicero Township west of Chicago, and in 1836 selected the present site of Austin as his homestead. <ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BE><U+00AF> There were then two roads leading westward <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+0088><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BF><U+00BC> from Chicago, the road to the Widow Barry<92>s house <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+00B5><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BF><U+00BC><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BF><U+00A0>on the Des Plaines River near Riverside, and Whiskey Point Road, now Grand Avenue. The Frink and Walker stage coach <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B0><U+008E><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00BB><U+00B4>rumbled through the prairies over its uneven surface. In 1848 the Galena and Chicago Union Railroad laid its tracks parallel with Lake Street. <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00BA><U+0082>In 1865 Henry Austin <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+00B1><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BF><U+00BC><U+200D><U+2642><U+FE0F>bought De Koven<92>s tract and laid out a subdivision with wide streets along which he planted hundreds of shade trees. <ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BC><U+00B2> <ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BC><U+00B3> There were 5 families in Austin in 1866; 8 years later the population was 1,200.<94> #archi_ologie #oldhouselove #chiarchitecture #thisplacematters #deserve2preserve #historicpreservation #archidaily #architektur #architecturelovers #architectureporn #austinneighborhood #austinchicago #historyofchicago

So, after stopping in Chicago<92>s Hyde Park neighborhood to buy myself stuff, I decided to head west and drove around Chicago<92>s Austin neighborhood. This home is in the 300 block of N. Parkside Ave. It was a last minute trip. So, I hope a couple (strong black women) followers who have invited me to hit them up for an architecture tour don<92>t see this and get pissed at me. To me, the Austin neighborhood is very similar in geographical size and scope to the Chicago suburb of Oak Park, Illinois. Actually, the City of San Francisco and Chicago<92>s Austin neighborhood are the same size. This home, however, literally costs less than a San Francisco one bedroom (or even studio) condominium. You can see similarities between Austin and Oak Park in the width of the streets and the style of homes. Both areas started developing around the same time. I have a ton of pictures to post, and I did stop in Oak Park to view some houses as well. Honestly, a good idea for a book would be a history of both communities, focusing on architecture, ethnicity, race, racial change, and stories from residents. Anyway, more houses to come. #austinneighborhood #austinchicago #oldhouselove

This small Prairie School church was designed by William E. Drummond in 1908 for the west-side community of Austin, then a suburb of Chicago. It was his first official independent commission.
.
Drummond served as Frank Lloyd Wright's head draughtsman during the first decade of the century; his stylistic debt to Wright is evident in the church design, which is related to Wright's earlier designs for Unity Temple and the Larkin Administration Building. Yet, the low bascilican church is an original work in its own right, with a low entrance set between massive brick piers, a clerestory lighted by a large skylight with lower side-aisles, and fine brickwork and leaded glass. In 1961 the building was named a Chicago Architectural Landmark.
.

<U+2015> Dietrich Bonhoeffer, Life Together

The church exists primarily for two closely correlated purposes: to worship God and to work for his kingdom in the world ... The church also exists for a third purpose, which serves the other two: to encourage one another, to build one another up in faith, to pray with and for one another, to learn from one another and teach one another, and to set one another examples to follow, challenges to take up, and urgent tasks to perform. Congratulations to six-time Emmy-award-honored television producer, author, and essayist, Linda Gartz, on the upcoming release of her new book, Redlined: A Memoir of Race, Change and Fractured Community in 1960s Chicago. Linda<92>s book exposes the racist mortgage policies, known as <93>redlining,<94> that ravage a Chicago community, told through the story of one white family navigating the uncharted shoals of its neighborhood<92>s racial change. Based on long-hidden letters and diaries, this vivid memoir cracks open and lays bare complicated truths of marriage, sexual freedom, and race relations in a devastated landscape. You can find out more about redlining, the book, and Linda at her website: www.LindaGartz.com. Her book launch will be at The Book Stall, 811 Elm St. Winnetka, IL 60093, 847-446-8880, books@thebookstall.com  on Tuesday, April 10th. Start time: 6:30 pm.

The city of #Chicago plans to build a massive multi-million dollar training center for police and firefighters in the #WestGarfieldPark neighborhood. But a coalition of community organizations contend the center will compound #PresidentDonaldTrump<92>s <93>multi-pronged attack<94> on communities of color and expand the #ChicagoPoliceDepartment<92>s <93>capacity for violence.<94> Last week, the city<92>s Community Development Commission approved a 30.4-acre land acquisition in a northwest industrial corridor tax-increment-financing (TIF) district in #Chicago. A $95 million <93>state-of-the-art<94> compound will be built by 2020 for police, firefighters, and emergency medical services teams to train together.

Mayor #RahmEmanuel hailed the facility as a destination, where out-of-state police agencies can send officers for training. It will spur <93>real economic development<94> with people from the suburbs and down state traveling to the center.

Similarly, Alderman Emma Mitts, whose ward includes West Garfield Park, asserted the community is <93>excited<94> about having <93>a lot more police<94> in the area. She also claimed there will be new economic opportunities. <93>I<92>ve lived there over 35 years, and it<92>s been vacant since I<92>ve been there,<94> Mitts said. <93>The community has been complaining about no retail there. So, I changed the zoning not knowing they were going to put the police and fire academy across the street. Hopefully, we can attract the retail they were talking about like grocery stores. They have to go outside of the neighborhood; nothing in walking distance, where you can get good produce.<94> However, Page May of Assata<92>s Daughters, who is part of the coalition, contended the compound is <93>an investment in policing. It is an investment in the #Chicago Police Department. This is not an investment in the west side of Chicago.<94> Debbie Southorn, a part of the #PeoplesResponseTeam, which is also a part of the coalition against the compound, said it is a <93>little bizarre<94> to believe a police presence will make the area suddenly appealing to retail. <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B6><U+0090><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BF><U+00BE>More in comments<ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+0087><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BF><U+00BE>#PoliceState #MinorityReport #PreCrime #RealTimeCrime #CitizenThreatRanking #Technocracy

They have to go outside of the neighborhood; nothing in walking distance, where you can get good produce.<94> However, Page May of Assata<92>s Daughters, who is part of the coalition, contended the compound is <93>an investment in policing. #tb to 5 years ago when I made the commitment to join these amazing 5 human beings in #intentionalcommunity to work on my self while serving others in the East Garfield Park neighborhood in West side Chicago. This year was THE most difficult year of my life. Adjusting to extremely new weather and being away from home for the first time but  it was also the year that put things in perspective for me. It was this year that I learned how to truly #lovegod and #lovepeople. Living in community was challenging but I came out of it being a better version of myself and even deciding to stay more years in Chicago. If you're interested in digging deeper into your passions and faith please check out @missionyear!!! its truly a life changing experience from a technology fast, to solitude retreats, to endless workshops and discussions around faith and social justice. Imagine what a year out of your comfort zone could do for you! In November of 2015, I had been living in Chicago pursuing a M.A. in Museum Studies with hopes to enter the Art History PhD program at UIC. I thought I could be a powerful figure for Museums/Libraries and cultural institutions. However, something didn<92>t feel right and I knew I was doing it for the wrong reasons, so I left Chicago after living there for 4Months and made the decision to live in the UAE. I told my family I would be leaving in two weeks. @miaangel_ being the sweet baby sister, let me crash on her floor and gave me the extra confidence I needed. I packed up two suitcases, gave away clothes and shoes to people in need with @ms_giannini, handed over my lease to a good friend @kellyeugenewilliams who needed a place at the time, and left the country with $400. It was the best decision I ever made. I had my struggles but the upside of all of this is so much more powerful. I just want to thank all of you and say how much I miss you guys! <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0099> You helped my transition and I can<92>t repay you enough. I wish you all well and I<92>ll never forget you. #NearWestsideChicago

This building now contains a caf<e9> on its first floor, but it was once the Vorwaerts Turner Hall from the 1890's. There used to be dozens of these Turner Halls in Chicago, but now there are only apparently two remaining (including this one). This Turnverein (gym union) can trace its history to Friedrich Ludwig Jahn, who was pissed that Napoleon's army was occupying various German duchies, principalities , etc. (no united Germany until 1871). Friedrich thought a physically fit and disciplined force could kick Napoleon's troops out of German speaking lands. I guess you can blame that little Corsican for these clubs. So, basically, when Germans started immigrating to Chicago, these sports clubs started sprouting up. Germans are all about health and schnitzel. The Hope Cafe donates what you spend to Hope Academy, which is a non-denominational high school. The school opened in 2005. #chicago #nearwestsidechicago #architect #turnerhall #vorwaerts #thisplacematters #historicpreservation #archidaily #architektur #archidesign #germanamerican #germanchicago

Here is a short video showing Notre Dame de Chicago. It is Roman Catholic and built between 1889-1892 in the Romanesque style. The architect was French Canadian (Vive Quebec!!) and named Gregoire Vigeant. It is located on the Near West Side (University Village area) and is at 1335 West Harrison. My buddy Sam married his wife Isella here back like 7 years ago. It's beautiful inside. There are not many (if any) French families in the neighborhood any more. It was October with snow on the ground.
Years ago, I'd ride the pink line to K-town.
In my favorite city<97>young & reckless,
evil wind within me, mind restless,
next 20-something up on death's list.
So much self-righteous hatred, 
only way I knew to cope was the dope, 
maintain to stay sane, 
wasn't funny how my life was a joke.
The baker's dozen for $100 a jab,
wrapped up and stamped shut, 
my lucky 13 bags...
<ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0089><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0080><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00BA><U+0091>

blessed with another chance,
to do this dance of life and survive.

Forever grateful to have escaped that trap.
Cost me millions in blood, sweat, and tears,
to buy my soul back.

Thank you, WBEZ, for sharing the story of how our site in North Lawndale, CYC-Sidney Epstein Youth Center (then CYC-ABC Polk Bros. Youth Center), sought to keep kids off the street during the riots that were catalyzed by the assassination of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.

Even on a rainy day, DRW (aka Power House High School) still looks good. The massive turbines in this nearly 115 year old building provided power for Sears, Roebuck & Co.<92>s sprawling West Side campus until 1973 when the company moved to its downtown skyscraper. According to the building<92>s engineer, at one time, hundreds of thousands of pounds of coal were delivered here daily, where it powered 75 foot high boilers (that<92>s insane!) and steam driven turbines. The railway cars full of coal would pull right into this area to unload. The giant original rigging system now supports the building<92>s fire escape. Not only did this project utilize federal historic tax credits, it was also the first LEED Platinum rated historic building in Chicago.

I was really, really hoping that this story in today<92>s @chicagotribune might turn the page on their historically negative coverage of North Lawndale and the West Side.  That it would step away from from the legacy of their American Millstone series from the early 80s... But, nope, the article takes a big <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+00A9><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+00A9><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+00A9> on the community.  Yeah, there<92>s a little more nuance, some askance looks at City polices/divestment but really it<92>s more of the same run on about poor black people, drugs, violence, and why can<92>t this place (these people) get it together.  You would think nothing really positive has happened in 50 years.  No Contract Buyers League, no civic ventures by the CVL or Black Panthers, no Homan Square, no Village West, no LCC, no Y Men, no Slum Busters (google Gerald and Lorean Earles), no Greystone Initiative, no K-Town Historic District, no redevelopment of the Original Sears Tower, no Power House High School, no Lawndale Christian Community Center, no Sweet Beginnings, no Cinespace, no Lagunitas (yes it<92>s in Lawndale), no strong bid for the Obama Presidential Center (at least not on easily dismissed or ignored). Nothing.  And all this happening despite decades of disinvestment by the city, crappy schools, and renewal being more synonymous with a bulldozer and vacant lots than real development.  Also, let<92>s not forget that whole Great Recession/subprime mortgage crisis that wiped out nearly a decade of community gains practically overnight.  Things are not ideal.  But there are good people here and this place matters.  It deserves better than another softball story.

The following pics and quotes is from a 2011 Art Journal article by Rebecca Zorach (<93>Art & Soul: An Experimental Friendship between the Street and a Museum<94>) on Art & Soul, an art space opened by CVL Inc. - the social arm of the Conservative Vice Lords - and @mcachicago in North Lawndale in the later 1960s.  First pic is of the Art & Soul storefront (now demolished) with a mural by Sachio Yamashita.  Second pic is of the two storefronts (a hat cleaner and a burglar alarm company) on the 1700 block of West 16th Street that became Art & Soul.  The third through fifth pics are of an open house and education programs.  Last pic is of the installation of Roy Lewis<92> West Wall: Proud of Being Black (1968). The collaboration ended with the first Mayor Daley<92>s <93>war on gangs<94> which some saw as being less about crime than crushing the organizing efforts they represented on the West and South Sides. .
.
<93>How did such a friendship come to exist? The Vice Lords, like other street gangs in the city, had become interested in working on neighborhood problems in a constructive way; they had <93>gone conservative,<94> and reinvented themselves as the Conservative Vice Lords, opening several businesses and sponsoring youth programs. Meanwhile, the Museum of Contemporary Art (MCA) was brand new, and its director, Jan van der Marck, was interested in how museums could make more of an impact in their communities<97>their entire communities. And so, ever so tentatively, this friendship formed, and produced an experimental art center called Art & Soul, at 3742 West Sixteenth Street in the neighborhood of North Lawndale on Chicago<92>s West Side.<94>
.
.

So...reading that paragraph about the CVL got me nerding out about their civic work in the late 1960s in North Lawndale again.  First off, here is the a pic of the Teen Town Ice Cream Parlor they opened at 3700 West 16th Street.  It is now a vacant lot (second photo) like most of the CVL sites including the African Lion clothing store, the House of Lords rec center, and Art & Soul an experimental art center that was opened in collaboration with the Museum of Contemporary Art (!!!). The third photo is in front of the CVL headquarters at 3724 West Lawndale.  That building still exists.  I wonder if it would ever be approved for NR or City Landmark designation.

Allium Cernuum or  Nodding Onion, is a wild self-seeding perennial. It can be found growing in rocky soils, dry woods, prairies & in the past grew along the banks of Lake Michigan.
<ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BC><U+00BF><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BC><U+00B0>
Its name derives from the umbel of small pink or white flowers that droop or nod down, distinguishing it from other Alliums. <ed><U+00A0><U+00BE><ed><U+00B5><U+0097><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0090> The stalk and bulb can be cooked or eaten raw just like any onion. Flowers make for an eye-catching garnish to any dish from salads, pastas & even sandwiches!
<ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0090><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BD><U+009E>
Nodding Onion is native to many states in the US and parts of Canada but is considered threatened in New York, Iowa and Minnesota.
<ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BD><U+0083>
The word Chicago originated from the Native word "Shikaakwa,<94> meaning <93>smelly onion". Wild onions dominated the banks of Lake Michigan and marked the area a place to harvest wild onions during a time when roaming tribes refered to places by what plants were growing in abundance.

We came here with @virgigi1 last month from her and her fiancee's well-deserved recommendation. Zaragoza's claim to fame is their goat meat tacos, and they did not disappoint. I wish I tried their quesadillas too, but the goat meat was all I needed. Their consomme was enjoyable (never had it before so I can't really compare it to anything). This all felt like warm food made at home with love. This was a nice surprise and #hiddentreasure! If you can't Google it, also try "Birrieria Zaragoza". <U+270C> Next time, I'll see if they have Chihuahua cheese too since I have a major weakness for Supremo. Can't wait to pimp more foodie posts in 2018!

Swipe left to see more pics. I have been through most areas of Chicago, but the Back of the Yards area of Chicago<92>s New City neighborhood is not well known to me. Chicago is truly a city of churches, and nothing makes me geek out more than seeing a cool building. This is Holy Cross Church, which was originally built by Lithuanian immigrants (#mypeople - my dad is 1/2) and dedicated on September 26, 1915. The Lithuanian immigrants who founded this church were blue collar workers, many of whom were employed by the Union Stockyards. In a book I own, <93>Heavenly Chicago,<94> author Denis R. McNamara describes the design as a mixture of Romanesque and Baroque. The architect was Joseph Molitor of Chicago. Some of the most beautiful churches in Chicago were built by broke ass European immigrants. There are no mansions in this neighborhood. It has always been working class. The Lithuanian and Polish Americans have been replaced by Mexican Americans. It has to cost a small fortune to maintain the church and school complex every year. Sunday Masses are only in Spanish. I<92>m hoping to check out the interior tomorrow and find some vestiges of the founding community. Maybe some stained glass in Lithuanian? If you see a well dressed Wero Instagramming like crazy, it most likely will be me. #holycrosschurchchicago #lithuanianamerican #newcitychicago #architektur #architecturelovers #deserve2preserve #thisplacematters #historicpreservation #backoftheyardschicago

Sometimes taking the <93>long way home<94> from the Endodontist (yes, the pain came back with a vengeance and I need a root canal) you come across an architectural jewel. Zoom in above the entrance to see that this was originally <93>Eglise St. Jean-Baptiste.<94> It<92>s located at the corner of W. 50th Place and S. Peoria in Chicago<92>s <93>New City<94> neighborhood. This is just 5 blocks north of Englewood<92>s Garfield Boulevard. I couldn<92>t find much online, other than that the parish began in 1892 but closed in 1989. The French are one ethic group which is not prevalent in Chicago, so it was cool to find this forgotten church with French connections. No longer Catholic, I have no idea what denomination now uses this church. Anyone know more about this church? #newcitychicago #newcityneighborhood #frenchchicago #eglisestjeanbaptiste #catholicchicago #churcharchitecture #architektur #deserve2preserve #oldhouselove #archi_ologie #archidesign #architecturelovers #romancatholicchurch

So, I'm waiting for the cops to come so I can file a report on a Peeping Tom/ potential burglar.

Last week I thought I saw someone at our window on two separate occasions ducking behind a mirror I have leaning up against the glass. I figured it was my imagination since our window is hard to reach from the ground.

On Sunday morning, I found that our fire escape stairs had been ripped off the landing and was positioned right under our bedroom window.

As a victim of stalking in my 20s and early 30s, this spooked me to my core. I am so grateful that our landlord is taking this seriously, in particular since our neighbours caught him on Saturday, chased him off and filed a report.

Fuck this guy. Be vigilant folks!
#shermanarea #hamont #gagepark #creep #voyeur #asshole #goodneighbours #psa

This monument to Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. stands in Marquette Park, in the Chicago Lawn neighborhood. It describes the day Dr. King was struck by a rock while marching to protest discriminatory housing practices in the neighborhood, on August 5, 1966.  The Martin Luther King Jr. Living Memorial was designed and constructed by Sonja Henderson and John Pitman Weber of the Chicago Public Art Group on the 50th Anniversary of the march. I posted this picture on my Insta-Snap but it's too good not to post on my Instagram feed. It's in the 6300 block of S. Western Ave, in the Marquette Park neighborhood (known also as Chicago Lawn). Marquette Park was a white ethnic middle class area, with the largest ethnic groups being Lithuanian. It started changing racially in the early 1990's. In the 2010 census, the area was 49% <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+00A9><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BF><U+00BF> 45% <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+00A9><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BF><U+00BD> 4% <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+00A9><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BF><U+00BC> and 2% <ed><U+00A0><U+00BE><ed><U+00B4><U+00B7><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BF><U+00BB><U+200D><U+2642><U+FE0F>. My Irish-American grandfather and my Lithuanian-American grandmother lived in this neighborhood before saving enough money to buy a house in the Canaryville neighborhood of Chicago, which is still an Irish-American enclave. Marquette Park didn't look like this when they lived there. And they were broke, having lost what little they had in the Great Depression. I'm sure they would've liked to raise their 4 kids in a free Section 8 apartment, which I'm sure now make up the majority of the apartments in this neighborhood. #marquettepark #chicago #chiarchitecture #deserve2preserve #oldhouselove #archi_ologie #architect #architektur #architecture #architecturelovers #architectureporn #ruinporn #urbandecay #whiteflight #lithuanianchicago #urbex #demolitionrisk #chicagolawn #marquetteparkneighborhood

\\Meet the @gechamber//
Racahael Turner - Director of Digital Platforms:
Rachael Nicole Turner is the Director of Digital Platforms for the Greater Englewood Chamber of Commerce.  Ms. Turner is an innovative and forward-thinking Digital Media Strategist and Artist. She is the Founder and Creative Director of both Rosemint Media (www.rosemintmedia.com) and Radiant Thorns (www.radiantthorns.com). She is a business and creative leader with seven years experience in the finance industry including a role as Registered Principal at a multi-billion dollar brokerage company and five years of entrepreneurial experience. 
Her entrepreneurial journey began with Rosemint Events, an event planning service specializing in wedding planning. In just 3 years, Rachael led on planning, day of coordination, or partial planning for over 25 weddings with the help of friends and family. After creating her business website and growing the Rosemint Events following to over 10,000, Rachael became intrigued with learning more on graphic design and marketing. Rosemint Media was formed and has serviced over 50 businesses with website creation, business planning, and digital media strategy. 
In 2015, Rachael received the @40under40ywpl and served as the Outreach Committee Chair. In 2017, she received the inaugural Member of the Year Award for the League and also become VP of Programming. Additionally, Rachael lends her digital media skills to a few non-profits and community organizations. Rachael enjoys painting, reading, traveling, creating, and helping others to curate their vision. 
Favorite Quote: "Sometimes you just have to jump out the window and grow wings on the way down." Ray Bradbury

\\Meet the @gechamber//
Felicia Slaton-Young is a founding member and Executive Director of the Greater Englewood Chamber of Commerce. She holds a MBA from Webster University and a BA in Management from Savannah State University. Felicia is a financial advisor with Edward Jones with more than 20 years in the financial services industry. Born and raised in Chicago, Felicia's family has lived in Englewood since 1983 and she is an active member and resident of the community, with 10 years of experience in fundraising, programming and relationship development.
Felicia is currently a board member of Dream On Education, Board President of Christina's Place Condo Association, member of R.A.G.E and past Director of Membership & Outreach for the Younger Women's Task Force, Chicago Chapter.
Relationships are key and Felicia believes building and developing strong relationships between businesses and community are vital. She hopes that the work of the Greater Englewood Chamber will be a strong advocate for pro-business policies that promote local job creation, improves the prosperity of our community, and serves as a unifying voice of Englewood business owners.

I took this picture a few weeks ago in the Morgan Park neighborhood of Chicago. This is south of 111th Street and on Longwood Drive, but to get to the coach house and main home, you have to drive on S. Lothair Avenue. Check out 2212 W. 116th Place in Chicago's Morgan Park neighborhood. I couldn't find a sales history online, but apparently it was built in 1937 and contains 1,980 square feet of living space. Ain't no way this is less than 2,800 square feet.  Especially when you look online and see the addition off the other side of the house. There is a tree to the left of this picture. <ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BC><U+00B2>There is also a side drive to the left. Blanche O'Shady lives here. She's now 75 years old and quite reflective on her life. She's put the home up for sale and has her eyes on a retirement community in Lake Geneva, Wisconsin. After giving birth to her 9th child in 1977, her uterus got up and walked out of her vagina. Never to return. Out of her 5 girls and 4 boys, she's closest to her daughter, Bronwyn. Why? Bronwyn married a plastic surgeon. Free Botox people!  Like most Irish-Americans from the Southwest Side, Blanche still has her First Communion money. Central Air? Why bother updating. Let the new owner put that shit in. Wood floors are the rage? Nope. Keep that shag carpeting from the "Swinging 60's" on that floor. Your bathrooms are yellow/grey and pink/white? Deal with it. Avocado green kitchen? It's called vintage, my dear. Blanche paid cash for her Cadillac last year, but refused the air conditioning. Such a waste of money. The car would've cost $40,000, and hey, that's how much she and her husband paid for this house in 1971 when the whole South Side was being panic peddled. And how could she spend the same amount of money on a car that she had spent on her house? (Blanche doesn't understand the concept of inflation). Travel? Other than the Irish-American summer home towns of Beverly Shores, Michigan and Lake Geneva, Wisconsin, Blanche has never been anywhere. Well, good luck on trying to sell this home Blanche. Thankfully, your frugal lifestyle will leave each of your 9 children a hefty inheritance of around $300,000 after you "kick the bucket." Here are two front views of the same house. It was constructed in 1951 and is located at 2200 W. 116th Place, in Chicago's Morgan Park neighborhood. Morgan Park is located just south of Chicago's Beverly neighborhood. Morgan Park is like Beverly's less attractive cousin. I mean, like, Morgan Park has some nice curves here and there, but she's pretty much a "But-her-face." The Morgan Park neighborhood is "good looking from afar, but far from good looking." I'm not a "Midcentury Modern" fan, but I actually like the look of this ranch home. ..
2 tbs Southport Grocery Plum & Lemon Verbena Preserves
2 oz vodka
1 oz Grand Marnier
 lime, juiced and a slice as garnish
..
Fill shaker with ice. Add preserves, vodka, Grand Marnier and lime juice. Shake and pour into martini glass or serve on the rocks in a highball glass. Garnish with lime slice and start sippin'!

During the month of April, healthcare professionals across the country are working to increase public awareness about the causes and cures for stress. Stress can also lead to a number of major health problems, ranging anywhere from anxiety to severe depression. All month long we will be posting weekly tips and strategies for managing your daily stress and learn to relax.  #StressAwarenessMonth

Tip #1: Get Moving 
Physical Activity results in increased levels of endorphins in the brain which is a great way to relieve and distract you from tension and frustration. Chicago's lake front path provides a beautiful setting for a morning run or an evening walk. Get out and get active.

Regrann from @drum679 -  Terra Cotta Row is a historic district that was home to employees of the Northwestern Terra Cotta Co., a prominent name in terra cotta trimmings. The company had extensive contracts with renowned Chicago architects including Louis Sullivan and Frank Lloyd Wright. The district contains a handful of houses and ornamental walls. This structure built by the company in the late 1880s contains many ornamental terra cotta elements exhibiting changing tastes of the day from Queen Anne to Vieneese Moderne.

Satisfied former clients called upon BGD&C when it was time to build a more spacious home for their growing family. The owners of our Lincoln Park English Home requested an entire floor devoted to entertainment. It consists of a game room with a wet bar, media room, exercise room, powder room, and roof deck with a hot tub. 
A few of our favorite details?  There is an abundance of natural light in this space from three large skylights and windows throughout. The sliding doors between the Game Room and Media Room were custom made walnut screens from our local millworker.

This is a summer sunset through the power lines in a Chicago alleyway. The alleyway behind my last apartment in Chicago, in fact. A place that was & still is so special to me. It's wild to think back to all the places you've called "home" over your lifetime. The memories made there & all the changes in your life since you lived there. I'm lucky enough to still be able to visit that beloved apartment & will be doing so in May. Looking forward to seeing my friends & my city after I take a trip around the country. It seems that no matter where my life takes me, Chicago will always feel like home.

ADRIENNE STONER

MAISON FERRAND

What made you fall in love with rum and when did it happen?

When I first started drinking I found rum challenging. The first drink anyone ever makes with rum is mixed with a bunch of canned juices, sodas, and artificial flavors. I discovered tiki bars through my time traveling in rockabilly bands and noticed that rum in that world is taken with much more consideration. It wasnt until Paul hired me that I had the opportunity to really gain an understanding of the spirit. When that curiosity peaked, my thirst for knowledge took over and here we are. Im a cane champion.

{The Getup} ed by many, mastered by few ....
Patience and the willingness to learn a SKILL is necessary in order to master this movement - and even then there is more to learn. A skill is the ability to do something well. In order for this to happen we must practice <daily or weekly> in order to get better + and for our brain and body to connect the dots. Heather does an excellent job of demonstrating the getup from start to finish. Have patience. Recognize you will need extra time with a coach, time spent looking at videos, and reading about anything you are trying to master.

When one of your Omakase courses is so good, you request it again to end your meal. This is THAT course! The fresh Hokkaido scallops at @raisu_sushi ranks up there in my all time favorites list. The fresh scallop (arriving directly from Hokkaido, Japan) is sliced thin and topped with a small dab of Chef Simons special garlic sauce. The creamy, almost melt in your mouth texture is enhanced by the natural sweetness and slightly briney nature of the scallop. Theres nothing else out there like this unusual and delicious dish! I also love that Raisu is completely accommodating to each diner. Ive been there with friends where we all had a specific budget and ended up with a beyond expectations dinner. Ive also had an Omakase experience where I told the chef to go all out! And it was INCREDIBLE! Hermosa, the birthplace of Walt Disney, is located on Chicago's northwest side. This densely populated neighborhood includes healthy public transit options and served as the headquarters of the Schwinn Bicycle Company. Development of this community sprouted in the 1880s after extension of the Chicago and Pacific Railroad continued through the community. From our historical collection: With identical visors, doors and body design at the front and rear, it must have been difficult to tell which direction the first Chicago Surface Lines buses were heading when they werent moving. In this 1927 photo taken shortly after service began, Twin Coach Bus No 1. Stops near the west terminal at Laramie on a short Diversey extension route that ran only from Harding. 
By 1930, the Surface Lines first trolley buses were operating on Diversey between Milwaukee and Narragansett. Chicago Motor Coach Company buses began taking riders downtown on the boulevard portion of Diversey as early as 1924.

Running out of ideas of who to market this to. 
You know the drill: Lease the building then sell it. 
#chicago #realestate #broker #belmontcraigin #commercialbroker #commercialrealestate #apartmentbuildings #apartments

Can't decide if I really want to take this listing... It's an old tavern that has been closed for some years now in the Belmont Craigin neighborhood. There are 9 apartments attached to the building which is great for income but the commercial space is really an eye-soar. 
Absentee/out-of-touch/out-of-state owner thinks that it could be converted back into a bar, it can't. They're not exactly handing out liquor licenses in Cook County. Furthermore, the tavern was a hot bed for nefarious activity, which is why it was shut down. 
I think this area needs something else other than the go-to for all commercial spaces in lower income areas (dollar stores, check cashing stores, liquor store, metro pcs, etc). With an owner that doesn't want to reinvest in the property to put it in sellable/leasable condition, this one may not be worth the hassle. 
We'll see... #chicago #realestate #broker #belmontcraigin #commercialbroker #commercialrealestate #apartmentbuildings #apartments

If you enjoy something really good, its always amazing to find it in another form, correct? I adore the Samoa @girlscouts cookie (especially when theyre frozen!) and when my foodie pal @chicagofoodiegirl treated me to the @maddiebirdbakery version of their Samoa cupcake, my reaction was completely  . Everything I love about the cookie is in this cupcake! Yes, a cupcake! Caramel cake , toasted coconut and dark chocolate ganache  are all incorporated into this sweet treat. Maddiebird bakery is one of the best bakeries in Chicago thats still a bit under the radar. Their custom cakes are truly stunning and impressive (check out their IG page!) but to me, its the cupcakes that stand out with popular standard flavors and special edition flavors like this one as well! Slow down. Its your turn, and YES, you deserve it.  Deep Dive: Savasana Workshop with Kristen Ethier

Saturday, March 31st
6:00 pm - 7:15 pm

Savasana, the sanskrit word for "corpse pose" or commonly referred to as "the final resting pose" in yoga classes allows us to exist in an in-between space between physical and energetic experience, between asana and meditation, between symbolic death and rebirth that is an inevitable part of our experience in yoga practice. 
More than a 3-5 minute time to relax, savasana can have a profound impact on our internal state and allows us to cultivate a deeper inner experience each time we come to the mat. In this workshop, we will explore the biomechanics and energetics of Savasana, practice a short yoga practice to warm the body, and experience a deep and nourishing 45 minute guided Savasana experience. 
Imagine a warm candlelit class ripe with both learning and experience, diving into the profound relaxation that already exists within each of us. 
Price: $25 
**Preregistration for this workshop is required at www.chi-townshakti.com

I will be the first to admit that my knowledge of SE Asia is severely limited. What I know of a country like Myanmar (Burma) is that they produce the worlds finest rubies and Imperial Jade. When it comes to their food, I have no reference point except that they share a strong connection to their more popular neighbor, Thailand. So, after reading an article by @mikesula and discovering that Chicago has a restaurant that serves Burmese Cuisine, I gathered a few pals and headed over to educate myself about this specific cuisine for the first time ever. The Family House Restaurant is located in the West Ridge area of Chicago, 2305 W. Devon Avenue. This unassuming little spot is truly family owned and operated. Their menu features not only Burmese cuisine, but there are Malaysian, Thai, and Cambodian dishes as well. I dont think there was any dish over $10, most averaging from $4-6. We asked the server for his suggestions, and he was happy to help us navigate the menu. One of the many dishes we tried was this noodle soup called Mohinga: fish soup with banana stems, onions, chickpea fritters. Its much lighter in flavor than the picture shows, but the delicate fish flavor is paired with lots of texture. The rice noodle was soft and filling, the extra squeeze of lime gave everything a brighter kick. Mohinga is considered a national dish of Myanmar  and is enjoyed mostly during breakfast. Id also recommend the Tea Leaf salad and their Roti with House lentil curry. If you find yourself wanting to try something different, or if youve been jonesing for some distinctive SE Asian cuisine, Id recommend a trip up north. Im thrilled that the food scene in Chicago is expanding this way!  #thefamilyhouserestaurant #thefamilyhousechicago #chicagoburmesecuisine #chicagomyanmarcuisine #chicagoburmesefood #burmesefoodchicago #mohinga #mohingasoup # #myanmarcuisine #Burmesecuisine #mohinga #westridge #westridgechicago #chicagowestridge #newtochicago #familyowned #familyoperated #obscurefood #trythis # #southeastasiancuisine #educatethrougheffort

This two-flat is in the West Ridge neighborhood of Chicago. It's owned by Asha Gupta's parents. Asha loves fashion. As a little girl growing up so close to Devon Street, its Indian-American businesses, along with her family's own Indian culture, really left an impression. Bollywood movies all day erryday. All day. ERRYDAY. Asha went to Parsons School of Design in New York City but returned to Chicago to start her own design firm. Now living upstairs above her parents, Asha devotes her time to her business, which is called "Sari not sorry." Asha loves to put various Indian animals on her saris. Elephants, monkeys, tigers, brightly colored flowers, etc. All are embroidered on Asha's saris. The only problem is that if you want a sari made, it MUST have an Indian  item embroidered on it. You want pugs all over your sari? "Sorry not sorry but this is my sari to design," Asha will tell you. "There are no pugs in India! But I can put an Asiatic cheetah on it." You want the Statue of Liberty on a new sari? "No, but I can replicate a bunch of Taj Mahals on a beautiful lilac colored sari for you," Asha will say. So remember, just make sure you pick an Indian themed item before you sit down with Asha. Or you'll receive a #sorrynotsorry instead of a beautiful sari. DISCLAIMER: the above is a  #storiesbysteve Read at your own risk. #oldhouselove #architecture #architect #archi_ologie #architektur #thisplacematters #historicpreservation #chicagotwoflat #chiarchitecture #westridgechicago #westridgeneighborhood

I'm at home watching the documentary, "Minimalism" on Netflix. I must confess; I have a lot of shit. Like....my one bedroom condo contains a lot of shit. I've tried to cut down on things over the past couple years and focus more on traveling and building relationships with others instead of going out and spending money on expensive dinners and tchotchkes. I love architecture and I think I post more pictures of these "old homes" because, maybe subliminally, these "old" homes have an aesthetic that is practical. Compared to many suburban developments, this home is small and on a teeny tiny lot. But it has character. It's not huge, so it doesn't have a huge tax bill compared to homes elsewhere. The heat and water charges should not be insane. I don't know. People are constantly saying I need something bigger than a 1 bedroom, but then I think of the added cost of more space. I need to stop caring about filling my place with "items." I'd rather travel. #westrogersparkchicago #westridgechicago #oldhouselove #archi_ologie #architektur #architect #archidesign #architecture #architectureporn #architecturelovers #minimalism #goals

This fish is on fiyaaahh  Every once in a while there's a restaurant that pops up under the radar & is easily dismissed as the cuisine is very specific and maybe not something the general public is all that aware of. This is one of those places. But this is also a place that can explode and become wildly popular because it's so different and delicious! This is true especially if you love trying something new or different. @abiteofszechuan is a legit Szechuan restaurant. Located in West Rogers Park, Chef Cheng Ding-guo is as Szechuan as you can get - he added sea cucumbers to his Shan-Jin baos! Alongside some more widely popular dishes like Cumin Lamb & Scallion pancakes - they're serving true Szechuan specialties like this whole talapia dish: served on a burner at your table; you can choose a wide variety of sides to cook in the broth (we chose crown daisy, enoki mushroom, rice vermicelli) - while the whole fish itself is cooking in the rich, spicy, savory broth! It's truly a delicious and fun experience. Real Szechuan food is known to involve a lot of hot peppers, but the peppers are used to flavor and not to cause pain  There are non spicy menu options available as well. Prices are super reasonable and portions are hearty. This style of restaurant is excellent for a group gathering, you get to try more dishes and it's a great communal meal. Staff is super friendly and helpful - Chef Cheng himself is in the kitchen crafting your meal with his wife - while the son and waitstaff are so eager to make your experiment a great one! Thanks to @amycookschicago for the heads up on my new favorite restaurant!  Head over here and give it a try before the word starts getting out! #abiteofszechuan #newrestaurant #newrestaurantchicago #westrogerspark #westridgechicago #chicagoszechuan #szechuanfood #szechuancuisine # #communalfood #undertheradar # # #sichuan #sichuancuisine #sichuanfood #sichuanpepper #sichuanfish

During the month of April, healthcare professionals across the country are working to increase public awareness about the causes and cures for stress. Stress can also lead to a number of major health problems, ranging anywhere from anxiety to severe depression. All month long we will be posting weekly tips and strategies for managing your daily stress and learn to relax.  #StressAwarenessMonth

Tip #1: Get Moving 
Physical Activity results in increased levels of endorphins in the brain which is a great way to relieve and distract you from tension and frustration. Chicago's lake front path provides a beautiful setting for a morning run or an evening walk. Get out and get active.

MARCH 2018 DAILY SKETCH | Tuesday through Saturday mornings, I wake up, make myself a cup of coffee, and draw onto one page of my sketchbook. Some days I feel good, but there are other days where I just have to force myself to put something on that piece of paper. Even when Im in a rush to get to work, Ill make it a priority to get it done. Other days Ill hate a sketch but force myself to keep it posted. I figured that thats just how life is. You cant paint the Sistine Chapel every day. Regardless of how I feel, I get the task done and have completed 87 daily sketches in a row. Hoping to keep this going at least till the end of the year. Thanks for following my progression. Happy Easter and beginning of April!

When I first spotted this cemetery on Foster, coming back from O'Hare Airport, still recovering from one of my "lovely" experiences flying transatlantic routes, I thought "wow, how romantic, a place for painters and poets!" By serendipity, after one of my enlightening dreams, I ended up crossing the cemetery by foot and finally realizing that in this context "Bohemian" refers to the czech region that I visited as a teenager when it was still Czechoslovakia. The Eastern European names on the tombstones did the trick! Of course, what was I thinking! #chicagocemeteries #easterneuropeinchicago  #northparkchicago

I broke away from my usual bone-in chicken pho at my favorite Vietnamese spot, Ph Nm La. I noticed the large table next to me ordered two of this dish, so I figure I would give it a try too! And so glad I did! Crispy yet chewy and soft noodles is the foundation for Napa cabbage, broccoli, baby corn, bean sprouts, fried cuttlefish balls, Chiu Chou fish cake and squid. A soy sauce based gravy pulls all the ingredients together. This giant plate of combination noodles will only set you back $13 - one of the many tasty dishes at this authentic North Park spot. #PhNmLa #northparkchicago #vietnamesecuisine #chiuchoufishcake #cuttlefishballs #combination #pho5lua

This house is on West Hollywood Ave in Chicago's North Park neighborhood. It's not that far from Mather High School. *Disclaimer: the following story is bullshit*  Wiebke Schnitzhausen lives here. Wiebke owns the premier lederhosen and dirndl shop in Chicago's Lincoln Square neighborhood. Wiebke is from Munich, and Errybody knows that Bavarians make THE BEST lederhosen and dirndls. For many years, Wiebke ordered her items from Vietnam, until the Feds busted her for opium distribution.  "Ich liebe Kokaine!!!" is what Wiebke would scream out when the packages would arrive. Well, after doing 15 years in the slammer, Wiebke was released and is back to ordering her fabrics from the Motherland. Sometimes she misses her "three hots and a cot"  and the Freundschaft she had with all her fellow inmates.  But she's 55 years old now. She ain't got time for that. Rumor has it though, that she'll be opening up a marijuana dispensary here in Chicago sometime soon.  And since hemp makes a sturdy material for lederhosen pants, she can use the excess for her clothing shop. Those Germans. So good at multi-kulti and multi-tasking. #storiesbysteve #northparkchicago #oldhouselove #archi_ologie #architecture #architektur #architectureporn #architect #archidaily #chicago

Happy 181th Birthday #Chicago !!! #Chicity is #MyCity grew up in #AlbanyParkChicago one of the most diverse neighborhood I grew up in

Chicago - My first true love. 
Its hard to know what to say about Chicago, because my entire adulthood has happened here. I graduated from high school in May 2003. On August 1, I drove up the Dan Ryan with my dad and all of my belongings in his tiny Ford Ranger. I didnt have a job or a place to live, I wasnt here for college, I was just here to be. 
So, here I am, all these years later, living out many of the dreams I had when I first looked out over the city from the freeway. 
For the last several months, Ive been adjusting to life in a new neighborhood - Albany Park - and living with my boyfriend - this view of our living room is one of my favorite things about this apartment. 
I also have my own workspace here, which Im still adjusting to. Having workspace, and having space in general. I was living and working in a studio apartment when I began bookbinding. You can swipe for a pic of my very, very messy workspace. #marchmeetthemaker #sweethomechicago #albanyparkchicago #bookbinder

Chicago Kalbi is a yakiniku (grilled meat) restaurant at 3752 W. Lawrence, in what was once the heart of Chicagos Koreatown, opened in 1990 by husband-wife team Isao & Chiyo Tozuka. 
Isao once ran a Japanese restaurant in Chicagos Lakeview neighborhood, in the far southeast reaches of Chicagos last unofficial Japantown: Isaos Place was located at 2854 N. Broadway, near the intersection of Clark/Diversey/Broadway.

When Isaos Place closed, Isao went to work at Itto Sushi, where he met Chiyo Kim, an ethnic Korean from Japan whose mother ran a yakiniku restaurant in Osaka. The two married and shortly thereafter opened Chicago Kalbi, a Japanese-style Korean BBQ restaurant in the vein of Chiyos moms. 
Over the years it has become a favorite not only of the Asian American community, but businessfolk entertaining international clientele as well as Japanese and Korean athletes playing in Chicago.

(Turtles, Armour Square/Bridgeport.) Ok, a break from the many Cubs-related pics, a short bar crawl in White Sox country, at bars in a business district I only "discovered" last week. I was biking 33rd last Sunday evening and noticed a Red Line 35th entrance on 33rd I'd missed, then two bars (and there's a coffeeshop on the way) across from Armour Square Park. Ended up there today, at Cork & Kerry on the Park then Turtles. Medium-size bar, open windows and outdoor seating because it's nice out, dog in the bar, had a Travelers Grapefruit (in a Lagunitas mason jar) then Crispin Pear cider (in Sox glass) because I'm still in a warm-weather fruity drink mood. Stayed for two to see the close Indians-Yankees game (NY finally won 1-0). #barsofchicago #chicago #southside #armoursquare #bridgeport #neighborhoodbars #sportsbars

(White Sox ballpark, now Guaranteed Rate Field, and photos of beer options.) It took me terribly long to get to my first baseball game of 2017...and it was the White Sox, though I live a few miles west of Wrigley Field and am a Cubs fan. It's just become difficult to spontaneously attend a Cubs game...but a Wednesday Sox day game vs Toronto Blue Jays was doable. Plus the food and especially the beer options are better at the Sox stadium. I biked the hour+ there in excellent weather, arrived a few minutes late (missed "O Canada," alas), bought a lower-level ticket in part because that's where the beer booths I wanted to see were. (And this way I wouldn't suffer the indignity of paying more for my beer than for my ticket.) I didn't sit down until the 3rd inning because I took a while walking the whole lower level. There are Bell's, Founders, Goose Island, Pabst, and Revolution stands with 4 taps each (and the large Modelo one; included a pic because I like the South Side/South suburban decor). Plus the Craft Kave with various brands in cans and on tap. When I have to spend more than I want to on something ($10 beer) I don't know if I should get a favorite I know I'll enjoy, or an unfamiliar variety because then I can rationalize the expense as trying something new. I went with a fave, Founders Rubaeus. At least the reddish beer would make a pretty picture...but it was served in a white cup. I sat for the rest of the game, which Toronto won 5-1, many happy Jays fans around, and moved on to other nearby drinking options (Near South/Bronzeville, not Bridgeport, though I'll do some bar crawls to post here soon...). After a stop at the Bee branch library (in one of my favorite historic buildings); it's the closest CPL branch to Sox Park, but had a big display up on the Cubs... #barsofchicago #ballparks #baseball #whitesox #soxpark #guaranteedratefield #craftkave #craftbeer #founders #chicago #southside #armoursquare #bridgeport

Armour Square Park at 33rd & Shields, listed on the National Register of Historic Places. This park has baseball diamonds, basketball courts, a swimming pool, and a number of other amenities. It's the center of the community and well-maintained, likely due to the park's advisory council. Good on them. Cool fact: This park is one of ten 'square' parks built by the former South Park Commission to improve living conditions in Chicago's over-crowded neighborhoods. If you visit the other 'square' parks like Cornell Square Park and Davis Square Park, you'll see similar field house architecture. These places continue to be central to their respective communities. #chicago #parks #chicagoparks #chicagoparkdistrict #armoursquarepark #armoursquare #southside

Another place I visited today at Open House Chicago 2017 was Rosenwald Courts. Originally 454 apartment units called the Michigan Boulevard Garden Apartments, it was built in 1929 at the behest of Julius Rosenwald, who was then the president of Sears Roebuck & Co. The complex was built as middle class housing for black people. Grand Boulevard had changed racially from an all white area to an all black area in the 1920s. The complex was not for low income housing, and was actually built to make money. It was an investment for Rosenwald. Some well known former residents include Jesse Owens, Joe Louis, Nat King Cole, Quincy Jones, Marla Gibbs, and Lorraine Hansberry. The complex closed in 1999, but as of 2016, it has been completely rehabbed and now has less than 280 units. The original architect was Ernest Grunsfeld, Jr. The style of the complex is Art Moderne. Swipe left to see more pictures. #artmoderne #juliusrosenwald #ernestgrunsfeldjr #michiganboulevardgardenapartments #ohc2017 #chiarchitecture #chicagohistory #grandboulevardchicago #grandboulevardneighborhood

Swipe left to see more pictures of Corpus Christi Roman Catholic Church in Chicagos Grand Boulevard neighborhood. #corpuschristi #grandboulevardchicago #grandboulevardneighborhood #stainedass #fxzettler #romancatholicchurch #ohc2017

Interior of Corpus Christi Roman Catholic Church, in Chicagos Grand Boulevard neighborhood. Construction was finished in 1915 to serve a wealthy Irish American parish. After the race riots of 1919 and resulting white flight, the area became all black in the 1920s. Joseph W. McCarthy was the architect who designed the church. Father Thomas F. OGara was the priest at the time of construction. The style is Italian Renaissance. The Sisters of Mercy were the nuns. The church was designed to seat 1,000 people. Open House Chicago is this weekend. I also visited today the Ebenezer Missionary Baptist Church. It was built as Isaiah Temple synagogue in 1899 for the German Jewish population in Chicago's Grand Boulevard neighborhood. Dankmar Adler was the architect. By 1921 the Jewish community fled and sold to the black Ebenezer Missionary Baptist Church. The interior, as you can see, is huge. Gospel singers Thomas Dorsey, Mahalia Jackson, Dinah Washington, and Sallie Martin sang here. #grandboulevardneighborhood #grandboulevardchicago #chicago #ohc2016 #dankmaradler

During the tour of Corpus Christi today, I was able to see the choir loft and the large stained glass windows. This is a close up of the center window. See those two old guys? To the left was the priest of Corpus Christie at the time of its construction and completion. (Anyone know his name??). To the right is Pope Pius X. Both scare me.  They are now immortalized in the windows, along with other Irish American parishioners who founded this church. They're watching you! The windows were created in Munich, Germany by the company of Franz Xaver Zettler. He lived 1841-1916 and started his glass design company in 1870. Please visit St. Michael the Archangel Catholic Church, which is located at 83rd and S. South Shore Drive, in Chicago's South Chicago neighborhood. That church is also filled with stained glass by F. X. Zettler. Herr Zettler always signed his name on the bottom right of his stained glass windows. While the stained glass by Zettler in Corpus Christi is great, the stained glass in St. Archangel Michael IS AMAZING. But visit Corpus Christi as well. #stainedglass #fxzettler #corpuschristichicago #chicago #grandboulevardchicago #grandboulevardneighborhood #catholicchurch #popepiusx #ohc2016

Checking out Corpus Christi. Interesting history. The church was built in 1916 to try to keep the white (mainly Irish) catholics from moving out of the neighborhood. But with the Chicago race riots of 1919, the remaining whites fled, and the neighborhood has been black since then. The whole area has been known as Bronzeville, which had been Chicago's Black Metropolis. Restrictive Covenants had kept blacks segregated to an area of Chicago's South Side known as the "Black Belt." Just a little bit of history for you. #corpuschristi #grandboulevardchicago #grandboulevardneighborhood #ohc2016

"This is the Gustavus Swift Mansion, which I just took a tour of. It's located at the SW corner of S. Michigan Ave. and 45th St. The address is 4500 S. Michigan Ave. It was built in 1892 and given as a wedding present from Gustavus to his daughter Helen, who married Edward Morris. Back in the late 1800's, Chicago, as hog butcher to the world, had three families running the show: Swift, Morris, and Armour. So this was a match made in pig heaven. The exterior is built entirely out of Georgia marble. To tell you how costly Georgia marble is, back when Martin Luther King's monument was being constructed, the designers naturally wanted to use Georgia marble to build it. Georgia marble, however, was too expensive to extract/obtain, so the marble used was obtained from Italy. This information was given to me by Mr. Perkins, who gave me the tour. Mr. Maurice Perkins is a veteran, former policeman, fireman, and now helps the youth of the community and former felons. The tour is free but you can donate. So I did. From my job as an attorney, I know it's difficult for felons to find employment after incarceration. The Swift Mansion is going to be open for Open House Chicago on October 15th and 16th, so go see it. And donate! Mr. Perkins is trying to do right by his community. The neighborhood was extremely expensive back in the beginning of last century, but following the race riots of 1919, the area quickly changed from all white to all black. After the Great Migration of blacks from The South in the 1930's, the Grand Boulevard neighborhood became the heart of Bronzeville. #swiftmansion #swiftmansionchicago #grandboulevardneighborhood #grandboulevardchicago #architecture #architectureporn #archidesign #oldhouselove #archi_ologie #chicago #meatpacking #1919chicagoriots #georgiamarble #chiarchitecture" #midmodmondays tomorrow

This is the John W Griffiths mansion, which is also know as the Griffiths-Burroughs mansion.  Mr. Griffiths was a wealthy white owner of a construction company who had built Chicago's Union Station, Merchandise Mart, and Civic Opera House, amongst other buildings. He hired architect Solon Beman, who designed what is now the neighborhood of Pullman, and also the Kimball mansion at 1801 S Prairie Ave, to build this mansion. I've posted pics of the Kimball mansion in the past. It's a cool chateauesque style home, so of course when one rich white dude sees and covets another rich white dude's mansion, he wants one of his own. I think the Kimball mansion is more beautiful, but this house is great as well. This mansion was built in 1892, when South Michigan Ave was loaded with beautiful mansions. Today, the Grand Boulevard neighborhood has many open lots with scattered sites of old mansions and buildings containing subsidized apartments. After Mr. Griffiths died in 1937, the mansion became the Quincy Club, which was a social club for black railroad workers. By 1930, the Grand Boulevard neighborhood was over 95% black. Mr. Griffiths must've been the last old white man on the block. After the Quincy Club, the mansion also was the first location of what's now the DuSable Museum of African American History. After the museum moved, Dr. Margaret Burroughs (who along with her husband Charles founded the DuSable Museum) continued to live in the mansion. Check out the online article by the Chicago Landmark Commission about the house. It even goes into the history of the chateauesque style of architecture. This is why I love the South Side. Architectural gems on the landscape. #february132016 #bronzeville #grandboulevardchicago #grandboulevardneighborhood #oldhouselove #solonbeman #johngriffiths #architect #architektur #archi_ologie #architecture #chiarc #chiarchitecture #margaretburroughs #dusablemuseum #chateauesque

This former mansion is located at 3800 S Michigan Avenue in Chicago's Grand Boulevard neighborhood. It was not built by Mr. Hunter, but Mr. Hunter used to live here. He died in 1999 at the age of 67 after having been a well known architect in the Grand Boulevard/Bronzeville area of Chicago. This area was also known as Chicago's "Black Belt," where, due to restrictive covenants, kept a huge portion of Chicago's black residents (many of whom didn't arrive in Chicago until the Great Black Migration of the 1930's) in a specifically defined geographic area on the South Side. #chicago #chiarc #chicagohistory #bronzeville #grandboulevardchicago #february132016 #chiarchitecture #oldhouselove #architect #architektur #archi_ologie #architecture #radcliffehunterhouse

Here is a local library at the SE corner of 48th and S Michigan Avenue in Chicago's Grand Boulevard neighborhood. Here is an excerpt I found in the 1960 Local Community Fact Book. The last pic I posted had an excerpt from the 1930 Fact Book. By 1960 the population was 80,036, after peaking at 114,557 in 1950. "As the Negroes moved in, the whites moved out, primarily to the new apartment districts of South Shore...Until about 1917, the movement of Negroes into Grand Boulevard proceeded without incident. Between 1918 and 1920, the area was the scene of conflict as efforts were made to keep new Negro families out of the district. In 1920, 32 percent of the area's residents were Negroes. Wow, check out the modification to the mansion on the left. I am obsessed with neighborhood facts and statistics. In the 1930 Local Community Fact Book, the census showed 94% of the inhabitants were black. 87,005 people lived in the neighborhood. Here is an interesting excerpt from this book from the early 1930's: "Negro residents, who had for some time been restricted to the streets west of State, began to cross that barrier in the early 1890's. Some of those who sought more desirable homes were John Bates, wealthy moving and storage man, who erected the Bates Building at 38th and State; John (Mushmouth) Johnson, at 39th and Vincennes; Dr. Perry who owned property on 42nd Street east of Grand Boulevard; Mr. Jones, at 51st and State; Fenton Parsh, owner of property on 42nd Place; Dr. Daniel Williams, Dr. Charles Bentley, S. Laing Williams, and Ranklin and White. As this eastward push gained momentum the Irish, German, Swedish and English elements were gradually forced out, leaving the community predominantly colored." I also read that as of 1930, there were 59 Protestant, 6 Catholic and 25 miscellaneous churches. There were 10 motion picture theaters, 1 ballroom, 4 fifth class halls, 2 dancing schools, 140 liquor establishments, and 6 liquor establishments with dance music. #grandboulevardneighborhood #grandboulevardchicago #historyofchicago #chicago #chiarchitecture #oldhouselove #architect #architektur #architecture #archi_ologie #1930localcommunityfactbook #greystone #chicagogreystone

Check out 4848 S Ellis in Chicagos Kenwood neighborhood. The home, known as the Gustavus F. Swift house, was built in 1898. Mr. Swift died in 1902 after post-gall bladder surgery complications. Flanders & Zimmerman designed the home. Mr. Swift climbed the    meat industry ladder until becoming a prominent figurehead. His home is a couple blocks northwest of the Obama residence. Want to see their home? Too bad. Its blocked by evergreens. Oh, and the street is blocked as well. Not very open, is it?  Want to see every nook and cranny in Chicago even Chicagoans dont know exist? Ive seen this house at 4857 S. Greenwood Ave many times, and finally was able to take a picture of it sans interfering greenery. Its the John B. Lord house. And it makes me say Lawd have mercy. John B. Lord was from Massachusetts originally. He became rich after partnering up and getting into the railroad tie business.  Wait! Not that type of partnership.  That type. The house was built in 1896. The architect was Charles Sumner Frost (1856-1932). Mr. Frost was famous for designing (along with Henry Ives Cobb) the Bertha and Potter Palmer mansion on Lake Shore Drive in Chicagos Gold Coast. That mansion was torn down. This one thankfully remains. It last sold in 2002 for 1 million dollars. Mr. Lord moved to the North Side in 1919, into a cooperative on East Lake Shore Drive. He sold this house for $50,000 to Louis Vierling, who also gave him the deed to his own home in Kenwood, valued at approximately $30,000 in 1919. So basically, the home sold for $80,000 in 1919, which is approximately $1.2 million in todays dollars. Currently, the yearly taxes are around $21,000. Mr. Vierling owned Vierling Steel. Of interest is that at the time of the sale, Chicago had a huge race riot in 1919, and the whites living in huge mansions along Grand Boulevard (Now MlLK Drive) were fleeing, with that neighborhood becoming part of the citys Black Belt, or what many call Bronzeville, which covered much of Chicagos Grand Boulevard and Washington Park neighborhoods. I wonder if Mr. Lord was concerned about racial change hitting Kenwood? Racial change didnt occur in Kenwood until the 1950s, when as of 1960 84% of Kenwoods residents were black. In 1950, 10% of the residents were black. Presently, about 67% of the residents of Kenwood are black. Wow. Who knew youd get a house description, sales and tax history, sociology lesson, and architectural history? This is 4806 S. MLK Drive in Chicago. I took this picture last Saturday morning. I tried to look up the details on this decaying mansion, but it looks like there is only information on the coach house on the property. SAD! Anyway, I'm chilling at a Starbucks in Evanston. I drove to Niles to sell some books at Half Price Books. After selling my books, what do I do? Yes. Buy more books. I bought a book from 1986 entitled, "Louis Sullivan, His Life and Work." Written by Robert Twombly. After hearing a lecture on the life of Louis Sullivan at The Cliff Dwellers Club, I want to know more. The second book I bought was by Andrew Alpern and is "New York's Fabulous Luxury Apartments." It's a 1987 reprint of a 1975 book and contains information and floor plans of NYC buildings such as the Dakota, River House, Olympic Tower, and other buildings. I love floor plan porn. It's an addiction of mine that I enjoy indulging in on occasion. It's 72 degrees out. WTF happened to a snow engulfed February?  I blame the North Koreans. #chicago #chiarchitecture #washingtonparkchicago #washingtonparkneighborhood #thisplacematters #historicpreservation #oldhouselove #deserve2preserve #archi_ologie #architect #archidaily #architektur #archidesign #architecture #architectureporn #architecturelovers #readingisfundamental

Engine Company 61
Built 1928 at 5349 S. Wabash Ave
This distinctive firehouse was the first of seven ornate firehouses built in the late 1920s during an important period of growth for Chicago. It is trimmed in terra cotta and ornamented with Classical-style details. Through their history and architecture historic Chicago firehouses like this one represent evolving ideas about the firehouse and fire protection in the City over time.

If youve been using shorter shears for a long time and are thinking to go bigger, good rule of thumb is to start with going up a half inch at a time. Our Haji Tribe is made up of powerful healers who have a dedication to health justice and community healing. 

They are folks who believe our healing is a necessity, a birthright and a huge part of our LEGACY as black and brown people. We have endured because we have ALWAYS BEEN HEALERS. We have always HEALED EACH OTHER. We have always known how to make it better + when we didnt, we knew where to go to LEARN. 

Haji Healing Salon seeks to inspire ALL of US to REMEMBER: We LIVE! We GROW! We TRANSFORM and we absolutely HEAL! And... the most radical thing of all... is for US to THRIVE, while living within a system designed specifically for our demise. Are yall ready to make THRIVING a form of resistance??? 


Sister Toni Lightfoot is a mother, an intuitive healer from birth, a trained + licensed Asian body worker + soon-to-be licensed acupuncturist. Shes also a Chatham resident, invested in contributing to a more peaceful landscape for her and our children. Recently, Toni made a monetary contribution to Haji Healing Salon that supported the purchase of our new FLOOR! This post (tho it got a little soap-boxy)  is in honor of Toni. Your support as a healing-practitioner + a Chatham resident is very meaningful and much appreciated. A deep bow for Toni + for everyone who has and will, support the growth of this enterprise.  Thank You.

TBT to that time in 2016 when I was inspired to collaborate with my dear sisterfran @yamaniyansa (and a few others) in response to Paris Hatcher of @harrietsrevenges call to build public altars, dedicated to Black Womanhood, all across the country. This old sign frame, from the abandoned Churchs Chicken on Park blvd. in Oakland, beautifully lent itself to our cause.


I miss Oakland, but I have a mission to fulfill in Chicago. Every day Im closer to providing a permanent sanctuary that prioritizes the  healing of Black women, men, children and ALL people on a healing path. The Haji Healing Salon will soon be a reality in Chatham. I am humbled EVERY DAY by this mission and doing all I can to bring this vibrant social wellness enterprise to greater life. 
You can support our move to 746 E 79th street by donating ANY AMOUNT to our website, following us @hajihealingsalon here and on FB. Coming out for services and telling your Chicago friends about our enterprise. It takes a village yall. Were grateful for your support. 
  courtesy of blackfeministfuture.org + Aya Nikole Cook. 
Oh yeah-Happy International Womens Day.

Haji Healing Salon is always attracting the most joyful + inspired healers!  Our new meditation teacher (and body worker) is no exception. 

Joshua is Senior Teacher of a moving  meditation practice known as TaoYoga Arts. Joshuas brand is Liberation Meditation and achieving mind-body harmony is the goal of this practice. It uses gentle movement, breathing, visualization + meditation, to balance, harmonize, strengthen + heal us holistically. 

Sound like something life enhancing? It is!!!Why not add another tool to that self care toolbox? 

Joshuas Buddhist and Yoruba background, as well as his commitment to assisting in our collective emancipation, inform his engaging teaching style. Join us tonight 6:30-8pm. Reservations required. Donate at one of 3 accessible levels to@join us! Liberation guaranteed! Cushions provided. Haji Healing Salon intends to contribute to a Bright Black Future for south side Chicago. 
Were in the process of brainstorming thru all the ways we can add value, inspire hope + offer very necessary alternative healing services for our community. 
Were bringing an herbal apothecary, affordable yoga classes, meditation class, acupuncture, reiki energy healing, Thai style bodywork, chair massage, astrology, tarot and African  divination. Well offer Saturday workshops with visiting healers, nutrition classes and continuing support in the creation of your healing lifestyle. 
If youre a Chatham resident, wed LOVE to hear what you feel would support this community (and ALL of south side CHI) in THRIVING! If youre a south side healer, we want to meet you! 
Post a comment and lets BUILD! 
Get a sneak peek at our new home when you join us for: The Bright Black Futures  CommUniTEA Brunch, Saturday Feb 24th! We truly believe this. 
We believe healing must be de-privatized. That life-enhancing and life-sustaining practices like yoga, acupuncture, reiki, massage + meditation neednt only be spa offerings accessed by the privileged. Our healing in these times is a fundamental human right and an absolute necessity.  
At HHS we offer healing services in community, so more people have greater access. We share the space, so we may lower the cost, without ever compromising the high quality of service. 
We are building a new model for community wellness that creates more jobs for local healers, more support for people on a healing path + a clear and affordable way forward, in the development of what we call a healing lifestyle. 
We win by prioritizing our mental, emotional and physical wellbeing. We win by inspiring others through our example, to do the same. We win by sharing resources, skills, time + effort to support our collective emancipation.

We all have a role to play and despite what weve been taught, we can ALL win!

Acupuncture does seem kinda magical. How DO these tiny needles inspire such a big healing response? How DO they get us to fall asleep almost every time we get in the chair? How can a 1hr treatment keep us feeling good days after? 

Its a good thing we dont HAVE to understand exactly how it works to to feel the effects. We just show up, relax and ALLOW the healing to happen. For real. 

We offer affordable, accessible community acupuncture with our skilled, licensed therapists. They know their stuff and theyre here for YOU southside Chicago! $25 1hr treatments Sundays 12-3pm reservations required. Book via link in bio. . .
Get poked and pay attention, you will absolutely notice changes within you. .

If youre new to our page: 
Grace Housing Complex is an economic and community development organization focused in providing low income mothers with affordable housing information services and other development opportunities within the greater Chicagoland area. We aim to create stable, safe, and healthy communities by developing, operating, and financing affordable housing for single mothers and children who lack the economic resources.
