Here are some pictures of my trip to Chicagos Roseland neighborhood yesterday. The first is of Christian Fenger High School. The original building was from 1893. The current building was constructed between 1924-26. Famous people who graduated from here are Eliot Ness (1921 - Federal Agent - Untouchables) and Robert Zemeckis (1970 - Director - Romancing the Stone, Forrest Gump, Back to the Future). Ive also posted pictures (swipe left) of some cool homes around the high school. The high school is HUGE. It takes up an entire block. Hardly any students are enrolled here. Something minuscule, like under 300. Back in the 40s through the 60s, it probably had over 5,000 students. Im serious. This high school is also infamous for the 2009 incident when Derrion Albert was walking home and was killed during a gang fight. It is alleged he was not a gang member but an innocent kid walking home who was beaten up when he came across the gang fight. Fenger has been an all black school since the early 1970s. Like so many middle class white areas in the late 1960s and early 1970s, the Roseland neighborhood went from white to black in less than 5 years. The most beautiful homes in Roseland, in my opinion, surround the high school. There are a bunch of craftsman style homes as well throughout the neighborhood. #roseland #eliotness #robertzemeckis #derrionalbert #roselandchicago #roselandneighborhood #christianfenger #fengerhighschool #chiarchitecture #oldhouselove #archi_daily #archi_ologie #thisplacematters #historicpreservation #chicagohistory #racialchange #whiteflight #architecture #architektur #architectureporn

Today I went with a friend to Chicagos Roseland neighborhood to track down addresses of her Dutch relatives (grandparents and great-grandparents) who used to reside there.  This #storiesbysteve is inspired by the 1937 Fenger High School Yearbook (The Courier) I found in a used bookstore. In the yearbook, under the pictures of the Seniors, are also their home addresses. I guess they didnt have stalkers in 1937. This home is where Ruth Brink lived in 1937. Its at 249 W. 114th Street. Swipe left to see Ruth Brink. A devotee of Jean Harlow, Ruth loves all things eyebrow. A hall guard, drama club member, and glee club member, Ruth is going places. A swell gal with a skip in her step, Ruth wants to be a career broad. Shes a tough dame, so shell be starting at (swipe left) National Stenotype Institute. At age 18, Ruth is getting a little long in the tooth. Half of her friends are engaged. She has a crush on John Lenally AND Bill Gore (swipe left). John is a tough guy who likes cracking skulls and working on Ford cars. Bill is more refined. He took Ruth to a jazz club (swipe left) all the way up in Chicagos Uptown neighborhood, which might as well be in another country, as its on the North Side and not in the civilized South Side. 1937 is such a long time ago. Lets hope that Ruth made the right choice in her career and love life and didnt become a floozy! (The last picture was in the 1937 Courier. I dont know who this girl was, but Im guessing she was a sister to the original owner of the yearbook. Her picture breaks my heart. I dont know why, but I collect old yearbooks from Chicagos neighborhoods and even cities I visit throughout the U.S.  I swear, Im not a hoarder. On a cold night like tonight, I watch TV and flip through these yearbooks, thinking about all these kids (who Im sure died long ago) and what their lives must have been like. Call me sentimental (or a weirdo) but its a hobby which keeps my imagination going). #fengerhighschool #roselandchicago #roselandneighborhood #fengercourier #chicagohistory #architecture #archi_ologie #chiarchitecture #racialchange #historyofchicago #dutchchicago #formerdutchchicago #ruthbrink

A trip down to Chicagos Roseland neighborhood should always include a drive through Chicagos Pullman neighborhood. This is the former Hotel Florence, built in 1881 after being designed by architect Solon Spencer Beman. Built in 1881, it was apparently named after (robber baron) George Pullmans favorite daughter. Its no longer a hotel, but since 1991 has been owned by the Illinois Historic Preservation Agency. Swipe left to see more pictures. Radius BEACON Thursday February 8 broadcast features Episode 78: Norman W. Long @normanwlong Calumet Project.
-
The three-part radio seriesCalumet Projectinvites us to contemplate how soundscapes define our sense of community. Each track exposes a complex matrix of networks that exist within the Lake Calumet region of the South Side of Chicago  specifically the South Deering community areas Big Marsh and Van Vlissingen Prairie reserves  to focus our attention on a landscapes diversity, restoration, and resilience. South Deering is a predominately Black and Latin neighborhood. It is also the site of the first steel mill in the Calumet region (Wisconsin Steel Works, formerly the Joseph H. Brown Iron and Steel Company), which operated from 1875-1980. Since the closing of the plant, the neighborhood has gone through an economic depression.
-
Radius BEACON is featured in "Sonic Arcade: Shaping Space with Sound" at The Museum of Arts & Design @madmuseum September 14, 2017 - February 25, 2018 in NYC.
-

ICYMI: Last week, we and Mayor Rahm Emanuel announced that we've selected a preferred alignment for the Red Line Extension (RLE)a project that will extend the Red Line to 130th Street from 95th Street. 
The proposed 5.3-mile extension would include four new stations near 103rd Street, 111th Street, Michigan Avenue and 130th Street. Each of the new stations would include bus and parking facilities. The project is expected to create an estimated 6,200 jobs.

Learn more about the project at transitchicago.com/redeis

If youre new to our page: 
Grace Housing Complex is an economic and community development organization focused in providing low income mothers with affordable housing information services and other development opportunities within the greater Chicagoland area. We aim to create stable, safe, and healthy communities by developing, operating, and financing affordable housing for single mothers and children who lack the economic resources.

This rare Frank Lloyd Wright home -- still searching for a buyer -- is now on the market for under $200,000. "One of the most unusual Wright designs in the Midwest, known as the Foster House and Stable, the house is a designated Chicago landmark and can be considered a rare Frank Lloyd Wright for a number of reasons. While Wright designed dozens of homes in the suburbswith the majoritybuilt in Oak ParkWright worked on far fewer residences in Chicago proper. And of the homes within Chicago city limits, one on the South Side is a popularhouse museumwhile another located on the far North Side is abed and breakfast.

The Foster House and Stable is not only one of just a few Wright homes in Chicago proper, but its the only Frank Lloyd Wright home in Chicago that is currently on the market. But theres more to the story behind this West Pullman house.

Originally constructed in 1900, the house designed for Stephen Foster, a real estate attorney who worked with developers around the West Pullman neighborhood. Fans of Wright may not immediately associate the architect with the house as it is certainly not characteristic of the Prairie School movement which Wright made famous during his career. Instead, this one features a Japanese-influenced flair and steeply pitched rooflines."

Photos, story cont'd at: https://chicago.curbed.com/2017/10/3/16413106/frank-lloyd-wright-chicago-for-sale

From our historical archives: Heading east on 120th from Morgan in 1955, a Green Hornet on the #36 Broadway (what was then the longest streetcar line in the city) begins a 24-mile trip to Devon/Clark. By the end of the year, the route had been divided in two, and streetcars were replaced on the southern portion with buses, which looped downtown via Wacker, Wabash, and Grand back to State. 
Until buses took over the northern portion of the route 14 months later, #36 streetcars operated south on State to Polk, looping via Dearborn and Kinzie back to State. Built by the St. Louis Car Company, #4396 was one of the last PCC cars delivered to CTA in 1948. Parts from 570 of the cars were later used by the St. Louis Company to build CTAs 6000-series rapid transit cars.

ICYMI: Last week, we and Mayor Rahm Emanuel announced that we've selected a preferred alignment for the Red Line Extension (RLE)a project that will extend the Red Line to 130th Street from 95th Street. 
The proposed 5.3-mile extension would include four new stations near 103rd Street, 111th Street, Michigan Avenue and 130th Street. Each of the new stations would include bus and parking facilities. The project is expected to create an estimated 6,200 jobs.

Learn more about the project at transitchicago.com/redeis
